---
export const prerender = true;
import Layout from '../../components/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout
  title="JWT Decoder & Security Analyzer — HeaderLab"
  description="Decode any JSON Web Token and analyze it for security weaknesses. Detects alg=none, missing expiry, excessive lifetime, and sensitive data in the payload. 100% client-side — your token never leaves your browser."
>
  <section class="tool-header">
    <a href="/" class="back-link">← All tools</a>
    <h1>JWT Decoder &amp; Security Analyzer</h1>
    <p class="lead">
      Decode any JSON Web Token, inspect its claims, and audit it against
      common security pitfalls — algorithm weaknesses, missing expiry,
      excessive lifetime, sensitive data in the payload. Everything runs in
      your browser; the token is never sent over the network.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="decoder-input">
    <label for="jwt-input" class="input-label">Paste a JWT</label>
    <textarea
      id="jwt-input"
      rows="6"
      placeholder="eyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJzdWIiOiIxMjM0NTY3ODkwIiwibmFtZSI6IkphbmUgRG9lIiwiaWF0IjoxNTE2MjM5MDIyfQ.signature"
      spellcheck="false"
      autocomplete="off"
    ></textarea>
    <div class="input-actions">
      <button id="decode-btn" type="button">Decode</button>
      <button id="clear-btn" type="button" class="btn-secondary">Clear</button>
      <div class="examples">
        <span class="examples-label">Try:</span>
        <button class="example-btn" type="button" data-example="valid">valid token</button>
        <button class="example-btn" type="button" data-example="expired">expired</button>
        <button class="example-btn" type="button" data-example="weak">alg: none (weak)</button>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p class="form-hint">
      <strong>100% client-side.</strong> Your token never leaves this page —
      decoding and analysis happen entirely in your browser.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="results" class="results" hidden></section>

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2>What Is a JSON Web Token?</h2>
    <p>
      A <strong>JSON Web Token</strong> (JWT, pronounced "jot") is a compact,
      URL-safe way to transmit signed claims between two parties. The most
      common use is authentication: after a user signs in, the server hands
      back a JWT, the client stores it, and every subsequent request includes
      it in an <code>Authorization: Bearer &lt;token&gt;</code> header. The
      server verifies the signature, reads the claims, and trusts the
      identity inside without needing a session lookup.
    </p>
    <p>
      A JWT is three base64url-encoded segments separated by dots:
      <code>header.payload.signature</code>. The header declares the signing
      algorithm. The payload contains the claims. The signature ties the two
      together with a secret (HMAC) or a private key (RSA, ECDSA, EdDSA).
    </p>

    <h2>Is a JWT Encrypted?</h2>
    <p>
      <strong>No.</strong> A JWT is signed, not encrypted. Anyone with the
      token can base64-decode the payload and read every claim. That includes
      attackers who intercept the token, log-aggregation systems that store
      requests, and front-end developers debugging in the browser DevTools.
    </p>
    <p>
      Treat the payload as public-by-design. Never put passwords, API keys,
      personal financial data, or anything else you wouldn't print on a
      postcard. If you genuinely need to transport secrets in a token, use
      <strong>JWE</strong> (JSON Web Encryption) — the encrypted counterpart
      defined in RFC 7516.
    </p>

    <h2>What This Tool Checks</h2>

    <h3>Algorithm weaknesses</h3>
    <p>
      The <code>alg</code> field in the JWT header decides how the signature
      is verified. A misconfigured server that accepts <code>alg: none</code>
      will trust any token, even one constructed by an attacker — the
      single most well-known JWT vulnerability. Symmetric algorithms
      (<code>HS256</code>, <code>HS384</code>, <code>HS512</code>) are also
      worth flagging, because servers that accept multiple algorithm types
      are vulnerable to <em>algorithm confusion</em> attacks where an
      attacker uses the RSA public key as an HMAC secret. This tool surfaces
      both classes.
    </p>

    <h3>Expiration and lifetime</h3>
    <p>
      A token without an <code>exp</code> claim never expires from the
      verifier's perspective. If compromised, the attacker has indefinite
      access. We flag missing <code>exp</code>, expired tokens, tokens
      issued in the future (a sign of clock skew or tampering), and
      excessively long lifetimes. Industry norms: access tokens minutes to
      hours, refresh tokens days to weeks. A 10-year access token is a
      finding, not a feature.
    </p>

    <h3>Sensitive data in the payload</h3>
    <p>
      Because JWT payloads are base64-encoded (not encrypted), placing
      secrets in claims is a common mistake. We scan claim names for
      patterns like <code>password</code>, <code>secret</code>,
      <code>apiKey</code>, <code>privateKey</code>, <code>creditCard</code>,
      and other red-flag keys. If you legitimately need this data in transit,
      use JWE or transmit it through a different channel.
    </p>

    <h3>Standard claims breakdown</h3>
    <p>
      The seven registered claims defined in RFC 7519 — <code>iss</code>,
      <code>sub</code>, <code>aud</code>, <code>exp</code>, <code>nbf</code>,
      <code>iat</code>, <code>jti</code> — get their own panel with
      human-readable times and explanations. Custom claims appear in the raw
      payload above.
    </p>

    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <h3>Is my token safe to paste here?</h3>
    <p>
      Yes. Decoding and analysis happen entirely client-side; the token
      never crosses the network. You can verify this by opening your browser's
      DevTools Network tab while pressing Decode — no requests are made.
      The analysis engine is open source at
      <code>src/lib/jwt-decoder.ts</code> in the
      <a href="https://github.com/kadirbg/headerlab" target="_blank" rel="noopener">repository</a>
      if you'd like to read it.
    </p>

    <h3>Why does the tool say my valid token is "expired"?</h3>
    <p>
      Tokens carry an <code>exp</code> claim with the expiration timestamp.
      If the current time is past that timestamp, the token is expired
      and a correctly configured server will reject it. The token still
      decodes correctly — expiration is a runtime check, not a structural
      issue.
    </p>

    <h3>Should I use HS256 or RS256?</h3>
    <p>
      For systems where the signer and verifier are the same service,
      <code>HS256</code> with a strong shared secret is fine and faster.
      For distributed systems where multiple services verify tokens issued
      by one authority, <code>RS256</code> or <code>ES256</code> is
      preferable — verifiers only need the public key, so leaking a single
      service's key doesn't compromise the rest of the system. Always
      configure your library to accept exactly one algorithm; never allow
      the token to dictate which.
    </p>

    <h3>What's the difference between JWT and a session cookie?</h3>
    <p>
      A session cookie is an opaque identifier that points to server-side
      state — the server looks up the session in a database on every
      request. A JWT carries the claims themselves, signed; the server
      trusts the signature and reads the claims without a lookup. JWTs
      scale better for stateless APIs; sessions are easier to revoke. Many
      production systems use both: short-lived JWTs for API access,
      server-side state for refresh and revocation.
    </p>

    <h3>How do I revoke a JWT before it expires?</h3>
    <p>
      You can't, directly — that's the trade-off for statelessness. The
      common patterns are: keep tokens short-lived (minutes) and rely on
      refresh-token rotation; maintain a server-side denylist of revoked
      <code>jti</code> values; or version the signing key and rotate to
      invalidate all outstanding tokens at once. Pick based on your
      security and operational requirements.
    </p>

    <h3>What does <code>alg: none</code> mean and why is it dangerous?</h3>
    <p>
      The JWT spec includes a "none" algorithm meaning the token is
      explicitly unsigned. Some early JWT libraries accepted such tokens
      by default — meaning an attacker could craft any payload, set the
      algorithm to <code>none</code>, and have it trusted. Modern
      libraries reject this by default, but the vulnerability still appears
      in misconfigured services. This tool flags it as a critical finding.
    </p>

    <h2>Further Reading</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <a href="https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc7519" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
          RFC 7519: JSON Web Token (JWT)
        </a> — the spec itself.
      </li>
      <li>
        <a href="https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc7515" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
          RFC 7515: JSON Web Signature (JWS)
        </a> — the signing format JWT uses.
      </li>
      <li>
        <a href="https://owasp.org/www-chapter-vancouver/assets/presentations/2020-01_Attacking_and_Securing_JWT.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
          OWASP: Attacking and Securing JWT
        </a> — practical attack patterns and defenses.
      </li>
      <li>
        <a href="https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc8725" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
          RFC 8725: JWT Best Current Practices
        </a> — IETF-recommended hardening.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Is my token safe to paste into a JWT decoder?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Yes, for tools like HeaderLab's JWT Decoder which run entirely client-side. The token never crosses the network. You can verify this by checking your browser's Network tab — no requests are made when decoding. The analysis engine is open source and inspectable."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Is a JWT encrypted?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "No. A JWT is signed but not encrypted. Anyone with the token can base64-decode the payload and read every claim. Treat the payload as public-by-design. If you need to transport secrets in a token, use JWE (JSON Web Encryption, RFC 7516)."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is the alg=none JWT vulnerability?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "The JWT spec includes a 'none' algorithm meaning the token is explicitly unsigned. Misconfigured servers that accept this algorithm will trust any token an attacker constructs. Modern libraries reject alg=none by default, but the vulnerability still appears in older or misconfigured services."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Should I use HS256 or RS256 for JWTs?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "For single-service systems, HS256 with a strong shared secret is fine. For distributed systems where multiple services verify tokens, RS256 or ES256 is preferable — verifiers only need the public key. Always configure your library to accept exactly one algorithm; never let the token dictate which."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How do I revoke a JWT before it expires?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "You cannot revoke a JWT directly — that is the trade-off for statelessness. Common patterns: keep tokens short-lived with refresh-token rotation; maintain a server-side denylist of revoked jti values; or rotate the signing key to invalidate all outstanding tokens at once."
        }
      }
    ]
  })} />
</Layout>

<script>
  import { parseJWT, analyzeJWT, type Finding, type ClaimInfo, type JWTAnalysis, type ParsedJWT } from '../../lib/jwt-decoder';

  const input = document.getElementById('jwt-input') as HTMLTextAreaElement;
  const decodeBtn = document.getElementById('decode-btn') as HTMLButtonElement;
  const clearBtn = document.getElementById('clear-btn') as HTMLButtonElement;
  const results = document.getElementById('results') as HTMLElement;
  const exampleBtns = document.querySelectorAll<HTMLButtonElement>('.example-btn');

  // ─── Example token generation (dynamic timestamps for realism) ──────

  function toBase64Url(obj: unknown): string {
    const json = JSON.stringify(obj);
    // Encode as UTF-8 → base64 → base64url
    const utf8 = new TextEncoder().encode(json);
    let binary = '';
    for (let i = 0; i < utf8.length; i++) binary += String.fromCharCode(utf8[i]);
    return btoa(binary).replace(/\+/g, '-').replace(/\//g, '_').replace(/=+$/, '');
  }

  function makeExample(headerObj: object, payloadObj: object, sig = 'demo-signature-not-verified'): string {
    return `${toBase64Url(headerObj)}.${toBase64Url(payloadObj)}.${sig}`;
  }

  function buildExamples(): Record<string, string> {
    const now = Math.floor(Date.now() / 1000);
    return {
      valid: makeExample(
        { alg: 'RS256', typ: 'JWT', kid: 'key-2026-01' },
        {
          iss: 'https://auth.example.com',
          sub: 'user-12345',
          aud: 'https://api.example.com',
          exp: now + 3600,
          iat: now - 60,
          jti: 'a3f5c7b9-1234-5678-9abc-def012345678'
        }
      ),
      expired: makeExample(
        { alg: 'HS256', typ: 'JWT' },
        {
          iss: 'https://old-app.example.com',
          sub: 'session-9876',
          exp: now - 86400 * 3,
          iat: now - 86400 * 4
        }
      ),
      weak: makeExample(
        { alg: 'none', typ: 'JWT' },
        {
          iss: 'attacker-controlled',
          sub: 'admin',
          role: 'superuser',
          password: 'this-should-not-be-here',
          exp: now + 86400 * 365 * 10
        }
      )
    };
  }

  const examples = buildExamples();

  // ─── JSON syntax highlighting (lightweight, no dependencies) ────────

  function escapeHtml(s: string): string {
    return s.replace(/[&<>"']/g, c => ({ '&': '&amp;', '<': '&lt;', '>': '&gt;', '"': '&quot;', "'": '&#39;' }[c]!));
  }

  function highlightJSON(value: unknown): string {
    const json = JSON.stringify(value, null, 2);
    return escapeHtml(json).replace(
      /(&quot;(?:\\.|[^&quot;\\])*&quot;(?:\s*:)?|\b(?:true|false|null)\b|-?\d+(?:\.\d+)?(?:[eE][+\-]?\d+)?)/g,
      (match) => {
        let cls: string;
        if (match.startsWith('&quot;')) {
          cls = /:$/.test(match) ? 'json-key' : 'json-string';
        } else if (match === 'true' || match === 'false') {
          cls = 'json-bool';
        } else if (match === 'null') {
          cls = 'json-null';
        } else {
          cls = 'json-num';
        }
        return `<span class="${cls}">${match}</span>`;
      }
    );
  }

  // ─── Render ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  function severityIcon(sev: Finding['severity']): string {
    if (sev === 'critical' || sev === 'high') return '✗';
    if (sev === 'medium' || sev === 'low') return '!';
    return 'ⓘ';
  }

  function renderStatusValue(analysis: JWTAnalysis): { label: string; cls: string } {
    if (analysis.isExpired) return { label: 'Expired', cls: 'status-expired' };
    if (analysis.isNotYetValid) return { label: 'Not yet valid', cls: 'status-nyv' };
    if (analysis.summary.critical > 0) return { label: 'Critical issues', cls: 'status-critical' };
    return { label: 'Valid', cls: 'status-valid' };
  }

  function renderClaim(c: ClaimInfo): string {
    const valueDisplay = typeof c.value === 'string'
      ? `<code>${escapeHtml(JSON.stringify(c.value))}</code>`
      : `<code>${escapeHtml(JSON.stringify(c.value))}</code>`;

    const meta = c.humanReadable
      ? `<div class="claim-time">${escapeHtml(c.humanReadable)}</div>`
      : '';

    const statusBadge = c.status === 'expired' ? '<span class="claim-status sev-critical">expired</span>'
      : c.status === 'not-yet-valid' ? '<span class="claim-status sev-medium">not yet valid</span>'
      : c.status === 'future-issued' ? '<span class="claim-status sev-medium">issued in future</span>'
      : '';

    return `
      <div class="claim">
        <div class="claim-name"><code>${escapeHtml(c.name)}</code> ${statusBadge}</div>
        <div class="claim-body">
          <div class="claim-value">${valueDisplay}</div>
          ${meta}
          <div class="claim-desc">${escapeHtml(c.description)}</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    `;
  }

  function renderFinding(f: Finding): string {
    const rec = f.recommendation
      ? `<p class="finding-rec"><strong>Recommendation:</strong> ${escapeHtml(f.recommendation)}</p>`
      : '';
    return `
      <article class="finding finding-${f.severity}">
        <header class="finding-header">
          <span class="finding-icon">${severityIcon(f.severity)}</span>
          <div class="finding-meta">
            <h4>${escapeHtml(f.title)}</h4>
            <span class="severity sev-${f.severity}">${f.severity}</span>
          </div>
        </header>
        <p class="finding-desc">${escapeHtml(f.description)}</p>
        ${rec}
      </article>
    `;
  }

  function renderResults(parsed: ParsedJWT, analysis: JWTAnalysis) {
    const status = renderStatusValue(analysis);
    const algDisplay = analysis.algorithm ? `<code>${escapeHtml(analysis.algorithm)}</code>` : '<em>none declared</em>';

    const sevCounts = ['critical', 'high', 'medium', 'low', 'info']
      .map(s => {
        const n = (analysis.summary as Record<string, number>)[s];
        if (n === 0) return '';
        return `<span class="sev-count sev-${s}">${n} ${s}</span>`;
      })
      .filter(Boolean)
      .join('');

    const claimsHtml = analysis.claims.length > 0
      ? analysis.claims.map(renderClaim).join('')
      : '<p class="no-claims">No standard claims found in this token.</p>';

    const findingsHtml = analysis.findings.length > 0
      ? analysis.findings
          .slice()
          .sort((a, b) => {
            const order = { critical: 0, high: 1, medium: 2, low: 3, info: 4 };
            return order[a.severity] - order[b.severity];
          })
          .map(renderFinding)
          .join('')
      : '<p class="no-findings">No security issues detected.</p>';

    results.innerHTML = `
      <div class="result-status">
        <div class="status-grid">
          <div class="status-cell">
            <div class="status-label">Status</div>
            <div class="status-value ${status.cls}">${status.label}</div>
          </div>
          <div class="status-cell">
            <div class="status-label">Algorithm</div>
            <div class="status-value">${algDisplay}</div>
          </div>
          <div class="status-cell status-cell-wide">
            <div class="status-label">Findings</div>
            <div class="status-value status-counts">
              ${sevCounts || '<span class="sev-count sev-info">0 issues</span>'}
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="parts-grid">
        <article class="part-panel">
          <header class="part-header">
            <h3>Header</h3>
            <button class="copy-btn" type="button" data-copy-json="header">Copy</button>
          </header>
          <div class="part-raw">${escapeHtml(parsed.raw.header)}</div>
          <pre class="part-json"><code>${highlightJSON(parsed.header)}</code></pre>
        </article>

        <article class="part-panel">
          <header class="part-header">
            <h3>Payload</h3>
            <button class="copy-btn" type="button" data-copy-json="payload">Copy</button>
          </header>
          <div class="part-raw">${escapeHtml(parsed.raw.payload)}</div>
          <pre class="part-json"><code>${highlightJSON(parsed.payload)}</code></pre>
        </article>

        <article class="part-panel part-panel-sig">
          <header class="part-header">
            <h3>Signature</h3>
            <button class="copy-btn" type="button" data-copy-raw="signature">Copy</button>
          </header>
          <div class="part-raw">${escapeHtml(parsed.raw.signature) || '<em>(empty)</em>'}</div>
          <p class="part-sig-note">
            Signature verification is on the v1.5 roadmap. To verify now, paste the
            token and key into your library of choice and check the result against
            the decoded claims above.
          </p>
        </article>
      </div>

      <section class="claims-section">
        <h3>Standard claims</h3>
        <div class="claims-list">${claimsHtml}</div>
      </section>

      <section class="security-section">
        <h3>Security analysis</h3>
        <div class="findings-list">${findingsHtml}</div>
      </section>
    `;
    results.hidden = false;

    // Store parsed data for copy buttons
    (results as HTMLElement & { __parsed?: ParsedJWT }).__parsed = parsed;
  }

  function renderError(message: string) {
    results.innerHTML = `<div class="error-box"><strong>Error:</strong> ${escapeHtml(message)}</div>`;
    results.hidden = false;
  }

  // ─── Actions ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  function decode() {
    const token = input.value;
    if (!token.trim()) {
      results.hidden = true;
      return;
    }
    const parseResult = parseJWT(token);
    if (!parseResult.ok) {
      renderError(parseResult.error);
      return;
    }
    const analysis = analyzeJWT(parseResult.data);
    renderResults(parseResult.data, analysis);
  }

  decodeBtn.addEventListener('click', decode);

  clearBtn.addEventListener('click', () => {
    input.value = '';
    results.hidden = true;
    input.focus();
  });

  // Ctrl/Cmd + Enter to decode
  input.addEventListener('keydown', (e) => {
    if ((e.ctrlKey || e.metaKey) && e.key === 'Enter') {
      e.preventDefault();
      decode();
    }
  });

  // Example buttons
  exampleBtns.forEach(btn => {
    btn.addEventListener('click', () => {
      const key = btn.dataset.example;
      if (!key) return;
      const token = examples[key];
      if (!token) return;
      input.value = token;
      decode();
    });
  });

  // Copy handlers (event delegation on results)
  results.addEventListener('click', async (e) => {
    const target = e.target as HTMLElement;
    if (!target.classList.contains('copy-btn')) return;

    const parsed = (results as HTMLElement & { __parsed?: ParsedJWT }).__parsed;
    if (!parsed) return;

    let textToCopy = '';
    if (target.dataset.copyJson === 'header') {
      textToCopy = JSON.stringify(parsed.header, null, 2);
    } else if (target.dataset.copyJson === 'payload') {
      textToCopy = JSON.stringify(parsed.payload, null, 2);
    } else if (target.dataset.copyRaw === 'signature') {
      textToCopy = parsed.raw.signature;
    }

    if (!textToCopy) return;

    try {
      await navigator.clipboard.writeText(textToCopy);
      const original = target.textContent;
      target.textContent = 'Copied!';
      target.classList.add('copied');
      setTimeout(() => {
        target.textContent = original;
        target.classList.remove('copied');
      }, 1800);
    } catch {
      target.textContent = 'Copy failed';
      setTimeout(() => { target.textContent = 'Copy'; }, 1800);
    }
  });
</script>

<style is:global>
  .decoder-input { margin: 2rem 0; }

  .input-label {
    display: block;
    font-size: 0.8rem;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    color: var(--text-faint);
    margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
  }

  #jwt-input {
    width: 100%;
    background: var(--bg-elev);
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 8px;
    padding: 1rem;
    color: var(--text);
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    line-height: 1.55;
    resize: vertical;
    min-height: 140px;
    word-break: break-all;
  }
  #jwt-input:focus { outline: none; border-color: var(--accent); }

  .input-actions {
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    gap: 0.75rem;
    align-items: center;
    margin: 0.75rem 0;
  }

  #decode-btn {
    background: var(--accent); color: var(--bg); border: none;
    border-radius: 8px; padding: 0.65rem 1.5rem;
    font-weight: 600; cursor: pointer; font-size: 0.95rem;
    transition: background 0.15s;
  }
  #decode-btn:hover { background: var(--accent-bright); }

  .btn-secondary {
    background: transparent; color: var(--text-dim);
    border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 8px;
    padding: 0.65rem 1.25rem; cursor: pointer; font-size: 0.95rem;
    transition: all 0.15s;
  }
  .btn-secondary:hover { color: var(--text); border-color: var(--text-dim); }

  .examples {
    display: flex; align-items: center; flex-wrap: wrap;
    gap: 0.4rem; margin-left: auto;
  }
